  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Frameworks and Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide standardized approaches to combating money laundering\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)\n- Extradition agreements\n- Information sharing between national law enforcement agencies\n- Cross-border investigations and prosecutions\n\n3. Standardized Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious Transaction Reporting\n- Customer due diligence protocols\n- Uniform standards across jurisdictions\n\n4. Regulatory Coordination\n- International banking regulations\n- Harmonized financial reporting standards\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering offenses\n- Coordinated enforcement strategies\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International economic sanctions\n- Asset freezing mechanisms\n- Coordinated financial intelligence efforts\n- Penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Technological Integration\n- Global financial monitoring systems\n- Digital information exchange platforms\n- Advanced tracking and detection technologies\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering internationally.",
